I'll help you understand the `@mariozechner/pi-tui` and particularly the `theme-lib` directory. Let me explore the documentation and files to give you a comprehensive answer.# `getSettingsListTheme()` & UI Component Patterns

## Core Theme Utility

The `getSettingsListTheme()` helper returns a theme-configured `SettingsList` ready for displaying toggle controls. It handles checkbox rendering and value formatting automatically.

```typescript
import { getSettingsListTheme } from "@mariozechner/pi-coding-agent";

// Returns a SettingsList pre-configured with theme settings
const settingsList = new SettingsList(
  items,
  Math.min(items.length + 2, 15),
  getSettingsListTheme(), // ← Auto-styles checkboxes
  onValueChange,
  onClose,
  { enableSearch: true }
);
```

## Main UI Patterns

### 1. Settings (Toggle Controls)
Use `SettingsList` to manage multiple toggle switches with automatic theming.

```typescript
const items: SettingItem[] = [
  { id: "verbose", label: "Verbose mode", currentValue: "off", values: ["on", "off"] },
  { id: "color", label: "Color output", currentValue: "on", values: ["on", "off"] },
];

// Change handler
ctx.ui.notify(`${id} = ${newValue}`, "info");
```

### 2. Status Indicators
Set persistent status text in the footer bar using `setStatus`.

```typescript
ctx.ui.setStatus("my-ext", ctx.ui.theme.fg("accent", "● active"));
ctx.ui.setStatus("my-ext", undefined); // Clear
```

### 3. Widgets Above/Below Editor
Render content lines directly in the UI for to-do lists or progress bars.

```typescript
// Above editor (default)
ctx.ui.setWidget("my-widget", ["Line 1", "Line 2"]);

// Below editor
ctx.ui.setWidget("my-widget", ["Line 1", "Line 2"], { placement: "belowEditor" });

// With custom theme/styling
ctx.ui.setWidget("my-widget", (_tui, theme) => {
  return {
    render: () => lines,
    invalidate: () => {},
  };
});
```

### 4. Custom Footer
Replace or enhance the footer with `setFooter()`. Exposes `footerData` with app stats like git branch.

```typescript
ctx.ui.setFooter((tui, theme, footerData) => ({
  invalidate() {},
  render(width: number): string[] {
    return [`🔧 ${ctx.model?.id} (${footerData.getGitBranch() || "no git"})`];
  },
  dispose: footerData.onBranchChange(() => tui.requestRender()),
}));
```

### 5. Custom Editor
Override the input editor for vim mode, modal editing, custom keybindings.

```typescript
class VimEditor extends CustomEditor {
  handleInput(data: string): void {
    if (matchesKey(data, "escape")) {
      // Handle escape
      return;
    }
    super.handleInput(data);
  }
}

ctx.ui.setEditorComponent((tui, theme, keybindings) => 
  new VimEditor(theme, keybindings)
);
```

## Best Practices

### 1. ✅ Always Use Theme from Callback
Never import theme statically. Use the `theme` parameter from your component's factory function.

### 2. ✅ Type Dynamic Border Colors
Explicitly type color parameters to avoid issues:
```typescript
const dynamicBorder = (s: string) => theme.fg("accent", s);
```

### 3. ✅ Call `tui.requestRender()` After State Changes
Always trigger re-render when data changes in `handleInput`.

### 4. ✅ Return Required Object
Custom components must return `{ render, invalidate, handleInput }`.

### 5. ✅ Reuse Existing Components
`SelectList`, `SettingsList`, `BorderedLoader` cover 90% of use cases.

## Example Files

| Component | File |
|-----------|------|
| Selection UI | `preset.ts` |
| Async Loading | `qna.ts` |
| Settings Toggles | `tools.ts` |
| Status Indicators | `plan-mode.ts` |
| Custom Footer | `custom-footer.ts` |
| Custom Editor | `modal-editor.ts` |
| Full Game | `snake.ts` |
| Tool Rendering | `todo.ts` |

---

What would you like to build? I can help implement:

- ✅ A custom editor for vim/emacs modes
- ✅ Status indicator with real-time updates
- ✅ Settings panel with search filtering
- ✅ Widget above editor for progress/todo
- ✅ Custom footer with git stats or token counters

Or let me know if you'd prefer more details on any specific pattern! 🎨

